    <fr:title text="Strong induction as well-founded induction">Strong induction as <fr:link href="jms-00NP.xml" title="The principle of well-founded induction" addr="jms-00NP" type="local">well-founded induction</fr:link></fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The “strong” or “complete” induction principle for natural numbers states that for any subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\subseteq  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  x\in  \mathbb {N}\mathpunct {.} x\in  S]]></fr:tex> if and only if we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\in  S]]></fr:tex> and, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m<n]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  S]]></fr:tex>. This is precisely the statement of <fr:link href="jms-00NP.xml" title="The principle of well-founded induction" addr="jms-00NP" type="local">well-founded induction</fr:link> for the <fr:link href="jms-00NM.xml" title="A well-founded relation on the naturals" addr="jms-00NM" type="local">strictly less-than relation</fr:link>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
