                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7720</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00NP</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00NP.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="The principle of well-founded induction">The principle of well-founded induction</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prec \colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } A]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="jms-00NL.xml" title="Well-founded relation" addr="jms-00NL" type="local">well-founded relation</fr:link> and fix a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex> holds if and only if for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x\implies  y\in  S]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>In other words, to show that every element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, it is enough to show that for any element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex>, the elements below <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> lie in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7719</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6093</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6093.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>One direction is trivial: suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex> and thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A=S]]></fr:tex>, and fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x \implies  y \in  S]]></fr:tex> holds. To show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex> we use our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>In the other direction, we suppose that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  x\implies  y\in  S]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>. We need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex>, we need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>. Suppose to the contrary that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\not \in  S]]></fr:tex>. Then the complement <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\setminus  S]]></fr:tex> is non-empty and therefore has a minimal element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>We will deduce that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex>, which is contradictory. By assumption we have <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(\forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  m\implies  y\in  S)\implies  m\in  S\text {.}]]></fr:tex></fr:p>

 <fr:p>It therefore sufices to prove the antecedent:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \forall  y\in  A\mathpunct {.} y\prec  m \implies  y\in  S
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>Fixing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\prec  m]]></fr:tex>, we see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> cannot lie outside <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> because it is smaller than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> is the smallest element that lies outside <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. Therefore, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  S]]></fr:tex> which contradicts our assumption <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\not \in  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
